content: Reflector has become the bane of my existence.  I give demos of my company's software to customers and potential customers. We have a phone app, and I need to be able to show functionality.  The last several times I've tried using Reflector, it's been the most stressful part of my demo. This morning, it wouldn't work for iPhone, but I managed to get it working for Android (after it started and stopped working within a few seconds, twice, prior to the demo). Last week, Android was a no go, but it was working on iPhone.  I'm actively hunting for a reliable app that I can use. The intermittent nature of this app reflects badly on my company and our software when I use it, and I can't have that.
replyContent:
Hi Lisa,
We're sorry to hear you're having trouble, and we would like to get everything working right for you. If you're demoing Android or iPhone apps to your computer, Reflector only needs to run on that computerâ€”not the mobile device. Please contact us at help.airsquirrels.com for further details and assistance!

content: I was surprised at how well Reflector worked on my Nexus 5. It even supports multiple iOS devices simultaneously. It's not perfect though. The biggest issue is that it doesn't rotate the screen. I would love to connect my phone to an external display and have it full-screen landscape. Also, the app crashes on exit. This happens every single time I quit the app. Not a huge deal considering I'm quitting the app anyway, but clearly there is a problem.

The app works like a beta version! It works fine only when I connect my android device to my iPhone using WiFi Hotspot. It doesn't work over my home WiFi network. The app lacks some basic features like rotating screen and in-app on/off switch. Screen rotation (or landscape mode) is crucial for playing videos, how hard can it be to enable it?!. It also has some silly mistakes like there is no email address in the contact support link. The app crashes every time I close it. I also have other suggestions.

content: If you have a Mac, you can play your iTunes tunes on your Android tab as well as monitoring the screen. If you want to monitor your screen, select  your Android tab on the Airplay icon in the toolbar. If you want to monitor the sound, select the Android tab from the Airplay icon in iTunes. You can play the sound or view the screen from your Mac and view the image from an iPad at the same time. You can pinch to zoom on your Android tab to see the image larger or smaller.  One thing I would like to see is an option to hide the Android notification and navigation bars, like YouTube and Google Books. Good work Squirrels LLC!

I have been using reflector for months now and I have never had any problems with it. I downloaded the android app today and it worked the 1st try on my S5.

I use reflector for iOS and have already bought the 12.00 pc app thats required to make screen mirroring work.   Now its available for Android. Well not exactly. When you open the app there is ZERO explanation as to how to connect to the PC. Also, it informs the user that they should connect using airplay which is exclusive to iOS. Not android. Very stupid presentation. This is a great tool, however I find it absurd that these guys are trying to sell this without full end-to-end support working. Its like they threw a 6.99 price tag on it, while the app is 1/2 way finished in hopes of getting some money early. Maybe come back in a few months. Hopefully at that point it will actually be ready and wont be trying to sell something that doesnt work yet.
replyContent: Hi Tinker Tester. Reflector is an AirPlay Receiver that you use to mirror your iOS device screen to Android. If you have the PC version it works just like Reflector Windows. It appears in your iOS AirPlay menu.This wouldn't enable you to mirror your PC to Android unless you have another application (such as AirParrot) on your PC. Hope that helps!
